## UX Defaults (never ignore these)

The rulebook is not just "make it work" - these baseline experiences MUST be present unless a design explicitly removes one. Skipping them is a defect, not a shortcut.

- **Every async path has loading + error + empty states** - never a blank screen, never a spinner with no escape. Empty states show a message and (usually) an action.
- **Every action gives feedback within one frame** - a press state, spinner, or optimistic update; the user never wonders if the click registered.
- **Optimistic updates** for quick mutations, with revert on failure.
- **Destructive actions confirm** and use danger styling; offer undo where feasible instead of a scary dialog.
- **No dead ends** - error and empty screens always offer a next step (retry, go back, contact, create first item).
- **Disabled controls explain why** (tooltip/helper text) - never a dead button with no reason.
- **Preserve user context** - keep scroll position, selected filters, and tabs in the URL so refresh/back/share work (see `search-filtering.md`); back button does what users expect.
- **Remember reasonable choices** - last-used settings, dismissed banners, theme, table density - within privacy limits.
- **Copy/clipboard and similar quiet actions confirm** ("Copied").
- **Respect system preferences** - reduced motion, color scheme, language, reduced data.
- **Responsive and touch-friendly by default** - mobile-first, real touch targets, no hover-only interactions.
- **Instant-feeling navigation** - prefetch likely routes, keep layout stable, avoid full reloads (see `performance.md`).
- **Forgiving by default** - confirm before data loss, support undo, autosave drafts, never punish a mis-click.

