## Toast / Notifications

Every mutation should have feedback (toast or inline per channel test above).

**API errors:** map to form fields when possible; toast only for non-field or unexpected failures.

**Accessibility:** toast region MUST use `aria-live` (polite for success, assertive for errors).

- **Success**: Auto-dismissing notification - `[DEFAULT]` 3 seconds
- **Error**: Persistent notification (stays longer or until dismissed) - `[DEFAULT]` 8 seconds
- **Info**: Brief notification for informational messages
- **Position**: Pick one position and be consistent across the app - `[DEFAULT]` top-right or bottom-right
- **Stack**: Multiple notifications stack vertically, not overlap
- **Colors/styling**: Follow your design system tokens (see `ui-design-system.md`), not hardcoded colors

---

## Theming / Dark Mode (IF your project supports theming or multiple visual themes)

Patterns for implementing theme support when your project includes it:

- **CSS variables** for all colors - avoid hardcoding hex values (makes theming easier even without dark mode)
- **System preference** detection on first load (`prefers-color-scheme`)
- **Manual toggle** that overrides system preference
- **Persist choice** in localStorage
- **No flash** on page load (apply theme before paint via script in `<head>`)
- **Test both modes** - no invisible text, missing borders, or broken contrast

---

## Accessibility (MUST in touched files)

Apply to every file the agent opens or edits for UI - not a whole-app backfill mandate.

- **Semantic HTML**: Use `<button>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<form>`, `<label>` - not div-for-everything
- **Labels on every input**: Visible label or aria-label (no placeholder-only inputs)
- **Focus management**: Visible focus ring on all interactive elements
- **Keyboard navigation**: Every feature usable without mouse (Tab, Enter, Escape)
- **Color contrast**: 4.5:1 minimum for text, 3:1 for large text/icons
- **Alt text** on meaningful images (empty alt for decorative)
- **aria-live** for dynamic content updates (toast, loading status)
- **Modals/drawers:** focus trap while open; restore focus to trigger on close
- **Icon-only controls:** accessible name (`aria-label`); tooltip SHOULD supplement, not replace the name
- **Destructive actions:** danger styling + confirm before irreversible delete
- **Escape key** closes modals/dropdowns
- **Skip navigation** link for keyboard users
- **Reduced motion**: MUST respect `prefers-reduced-motion` - provide static alternative
- **Empty states**: MUST show message ± action when lists/grids have zero results - not blank UI
- **Error boundaries**: PREFER per route/feature segment - not only a root error page

---

## Animations

- **Purposeful only** - animation must communicate something (entry, exit, state change)
- **Fast**: 100-200ms for UI feedback (hover, toggle), 200-300ms for page transitions - use your project's defined duration tokens consistently
- **Ease curves**: ease-out for entries, ease-in for exits
- **No animation** for reduced-motion preference
- **Never block interaction** waiting for animation to finish
- **Consistent** - same type of elements animate the same way everywhere

---

## Server-Side Data Bootstrap (SSR / RSC)

IF your framework supports server-side rendering or server components, pass **initial data** from server to client to avoid redundant fetches on hydration:

```
Pattern:
  Server Component / getServerSideProps:
    -> Load current session + permissions + initial data in parallel
    -> Pass as props / initialData to client Provider components

  Client Provider:
    -> Accepts initialData prop
    -> Uses it as starting cache value (skip first fetch)
    -> Revalidates in background as normal
```

- Fetch auth state + initial data in a single `Promise.all` on the server - don't waterfall
- Client providers should accept `initialData` and treat it as pre-filled cache
- The client still revalidates normally after hydration - the bootstrap just prevents a loading flash
- Keep server-only imports (DB, secrets) out of shared code - use dynamic imports or separate files if needed

---

## Client-Side Data Cache (Inflight Deduplication)

Whether you use a library (SWR, React Query, Apollo) or a custom hook, your client data layer should handle:

```
Requirements:
  1. Cache by key      -> same key returns cached data instantly
  2. Stale time        -> cached data older than N seconds triggers background refetch
  3. Inflight dedup    -> 5 components requesting the same key = 1 HTTP call
  4. Invalidation      -> after a mutation, invalidate related cache keys (by prefix or exact)
  5. Subscribers       -> components re-render when their key's data changes
```

- Every data-fetching component uses the same cache layer - never mix raw `fetch` and cached hooks
- Invalidation by key prefix (e.g., invalidate all keys starting with `resources:`) after mutations
- Prefetch on hover/focus for likely navigation targets (reuses the same cache)
- On session end, clear the entire cache

### Polling: One Subscriber, Many Consumers

When several mounted components need the same periodically-refreshed data (unread counts, chat/notification badges, live status, presence), do NOT let each component run its own `setInterval` + fetch. That multiplies identical requests by the number of mounts.

- **Single shared poller** - one interval per data key (in a context/provider, store, or a module-level singleton). Mounted components subscribe and read from it; they do not each poll.
- **Reference-count the interval** - start the timer when the first subscriber mounts, stop it when the last unmounts. No background polling with zero consumers.
- **Pause when hidden** - stop or slow the poll while the tab is backgrounded (`visibilitychange`); resume + refetch immediately on focus.
- **Prefer push when it exists** - if the data has a realtime channel (WebSocket/SSE), use it instead of polling (see `realtime.md`); poll only as a fallback.
- **Back off on error** - on repeated failures, widen the interval instead of hammering the server.

